newsitem.title: MALAYSIA: Malaysia palm oil ends firmer on refiner covering.
newsitem.headline: Malaysia palm oil ends firmer on refiner covering.

text.p: PALM OIL FUTURES PALM OIL PHYSICAL
Jan (3rd pos) 1147 rgt/tonne Nov (south) 1175
Open/Hi/low 1125/1148/1125 Prev close 1160
Prev settlement 1128 * sellers prices
PALM OIL FUTURES - Prices ended higher, helped by short-covering from refiners. Next resistance seen at 1170-1180 ringgit. Market firm and awaiting full export data for October.
PALM OIL PHYSICAL - Prices also firmed but trading still generally thin and focussed on crude palm oil.
Malaysian palm oil prices ended higher after covering by refiners and confidence that the market will surge until the release of full export data for October on Friday, traders said.
But a correction was likely soon after, as the market had little fundamentals to trade on, they said.
"The market's picking up and it's firm. It's probably riding on the steam of export figures which will be out end of the month," said a trader.
Another dealer said third position January futures could climb another 30 to 40 ringgit by Friday.
"I think the next resistance is between 1,170 and 1,180," said the dealer. "But there's not enough incentive to support the price at this level."
Traders said Tuesday's buying was believed to be mostly covering by refiners, which led to higher prices in both the physical and futures market.
"I think prices will fall back once the refiners' covering is over," said another trader. He said market players were still concerned over the near-term fundamental outlook.
Demand is likely to slow down over the next two months which could lead to a further build-up in domestic stocks.
Traders said players were awaiting the release of October export data from cargo surveyors Societe Generale de Surveillance (SGS) and Caleb Brett later in the week.
SGS on Monday estimated Malaysia's palm oil exports for October 1-25 at 615,327 tonnes compared with 528,150 tonnes for September 1-25.
Palm oil stocks at the end of September stood at 894,030 tonnes, the Palm Oil Registration and Licensing Authority figures showed.
January crude palm oil futures closed at 1,147 ringgit ($456.61) a tonne, up 19 ringgit.
Turnover on the futures market was 1,401 lots against 1,047 on Monday.
Physical Nov (south) crude palm oil was offered at 1,175 ringgit ($467.75) a tonne, up 15 ringgit from Monday, with bids at 1,160.
Nov (central) was offered at 1,155 with bids at 1,145, and Nov (north) saw offers at 1,145 and bids at 1,135.
Dec (south) was offered at 1,175 ringgit with bids at 1,170. Dec (central) saw offers at 1,160 and bids at 1,150.
Among refined products, Nov RBD palm olein was offered at $535 a tonne FOB Malaysia, and Dec to Mar at $532.50.
Nov to Mar RBD palm oil were offered at $500.
Nov RBD palm stearin saw sellers at $375 and Dec at $377.50.
-- Barani Krishnaan (603-230-7509) ($1=2.5120 ringgit)
